Reasoning: The paper proposes a framework for task-oriented grasping and evaluates its effectiveness in both perfect information and partial information contexts. This involves the use of basic grasp metrics and deep learning models to infer task-oriented metrics from vision. The paper's focus on robotics and computer vision, as well as its use of deep learning models, suggests that it is most likely to belong to the cs.RO (Robotics) and cs.CV (Computer Vision) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper's use of machine learning models for inference suggests that it may also belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-categories. Finally, the paper's focus on grasping and manipulation tasks suggests that it may also belong to the cs.ROBOTS (Robotics and Automation) sub-category.
